The moon outshone the stars and turned the gallows silver. Matthis watched the dead wizard's flesh and clothing slip off its black skeleton into a pipe at its feet. When the last of its face squelched to the ground, it didn't flinch or stumble. It stood, black eye sockets trained toward the gibbets, its bones visible only by its moonlit outline. It slid its bones out of its boots. It did not wobble. It stepped around its pile of clothes and rotten meat.

Matthis would have to burn the clothes and other remains later. He thought of the girl, Aura. The moment he touched her hand, something in him had ripped. His bones still ached.

Matthis felt in his satchel for the book, but he must have pulled it into his lap and forgotten. He stared at the gallows. He had almost joined those gibbets. 

He opened the book to a blank page. "What am I?" he whispered. 

A man lifts his hands before thousands. They fall to their knees. 

Matthis stared. He turned the page. 

"No."

Before he could consider his next question, footsteps echoed from the square. His ears were sharper than usual. He tucked the book in his satchel before it could be seen. 

"You always work the night after you save a village?" Rafe sat next to Matthis. "When I told you to make friends, I didn't expect you to do --" He gestured at the wizard. "-- that."

"You spoke up," said Matthis. Aside from the ache in his bones, he felt a knot in his chest. "For me. This morning."

Rafe waved the thought away. "Cartload of good that did. If you hadn't --" Rafe searched for words. "-- done whatever it was you did, they would have strung you up. No matter what I said." He clenched his fists. 

An owl blinked at them from atop the gallows. It raised its wings and melted into shadow. 

"Tell me," said Rafe, his tone soft, his hands relaxed in his lap, "what I saw today, Matthis." He searched Matthis' eyes for something. "What did you do?"

Matthis looked at his hands. Pale as bone in the moonlight. He remembered the way Aura's little fingers closed around his thumb.

"I held her hand."

Rafe's eyes were brown, even when washed out by moonlight. They softened when he smiled. 

"It scared everyone," he said. "And you stopped it."

They shared a look. Rafe nodded. Matthis hesitated, then nodded back. They sat in the dirt. A hoot echoed from the treeline. The wizard moaned. 

"It's all bone," said Rafe, "so how is it still making noise?"

"Yeah." Matthis poked a little pile of dust he had made, and it toppled. "Keeps doing that."

Rafe bounced to his feet. With an absurd grin, he extended a hand. 

"Do you want to help finish Goodman Morell's grave?"

Matthis looked at Rafe's hand. In the last two months, this would be the third living human he had touched. He took Rafe's hand. Nothing happened. Rafe pulled him to his feet. The ache in his bones was still there. But it seemed a little more bearable. 

A gentle breeze blew a bit of dust off their shoulders. It brought a sweet smell of pine and flowers. 

"Yeah," said Matthis. "Let's go."

--

Matthis and Rafe took turns in the grave. The dead wizard stood over them, but its sockets still faced the gallows. Matthis sat with his legs dangling in the neck-deep hole. 

"Do you always save the grave digging until the burial?" 

Rafe chucked dirt in his direction. "Matthis making jokes?"

Matthis grinned. Rafe pointed at him.

"I saw that. Can't deny it now."

Matthis jumped in and took the shovel. "My turn."

Matthis lost himself in the rhythm. Rafe didn't correct anything or watch. He rested his hands on his hips and threw his head back to look at the moon. Crickets chirped a tuneless melody. Bats crossed the moon. 

"Wonder if we'll see any," said Rafe. 

Matthis grunted. 

"Good question," said Rafe. "I don't know what they are, exactly."

Matthis leaned on the shovel. Rafe looked down at him. Matthis raised his eyebrows. 

"You've never seen them? They look like fireflies," Rafe explained. "They love nights like this."

Matthis resumed the dig. The crickets intensified. The wizard groaned. A warm breeze ruffled Matthis' hair. 

A tiny ball of light dropped out of the moon. Matthis stared. The little ball landed on Rafe's shoulder. 

"You've got one."

Rafe laughed and held up his hand to his shoulder. The ball of light drifted onto his palm. Rafe held it close to his nose. Then he squatted and held it out to Matthis.

"Look at it."

It was a person the size of a blueberry. Its eyes were large for its size. It didn't walk. It flowed, like dancing. And it didn't seem quite solid. It left streaks of light that faded quickly behind it. Its hair was white.

"Is it a fairy?" Matthis whispered.

"I don't know," whispered Rafe.

The little ball of light floated off Rafe's hand and vanished into the stars. The insects settled into a calm rhythm. Crick-crick, crick-crick.

"I wonder what else is out there," whispered Matthis. 

He and Rafe looked at the stars for a while. More bats flitted in and out of the moon and made stars blink. Warm winds hissed through calm, distant trees. An owl's hoot echoed through the village.

"Get up," said Rafe. "My turn again."

Matthis stood by the wizard while Rafe dug. He couldn't see the gallows from here, but the wizard seemed to see it anyway. He couldn't see the skeleton next to him unless he focused. The wizard skeleton groaned. 

From here, Matthis could see the parts of the village more clearly. The smithy, the Oak and Ember, the church and morgue, and a few squat houses formed a square on the old side of the village. The new part of the village looked like timber frame hostels and miner's barracks stacked too close together. Some leaned against a neighboring house or building. On a flat area below the mine, the guild house and warehouses formed the yard, where coal was broken and loaded into wagons. The lime kiln stood like a tall chimney by the slack heap. Near the mine entrance hung the pit bell. It served many purposes. A year ago, it had alerted the village of the cave in. 

Matthis didn't jump when Rafe touched his shoulder. But he did stiffen his jaw. 

"Matthis why don't you go home? I think I have the rest of this."

Matthis inspected the hole. With an easy grin, Rafe folded his arms beside him. Matthis jumped in.

"I hadn't expected so much progress." 

"Its not my first grave, Death Guild Master." 

Matthis glared and Rafe laughed. Matthis had to jump to pull himself out. The earth smelled old but clean. Matthis brushed himself off. 

Rafe thanked him. They shook hands. Rafe's hand was warm. 

"Next time," said Rafe, "we should visit the Hollow."

"Next time?"

Rafe smiled. Matthis looked at him. And grinned.

--

Matthis and the wizard walked back to the Death Guild hut. The moon dipped below the Blackvein peaks. For some time, he only heard the click of the wizard's feet and the crunch of his own boots.  When they reached the gallows, the wizard stood next to its pile of clothes and discarded flesh.

Matthis sat down and pulled the black book from his satchel. He tapped it and formed his question. He thought about Aura, the fairy, the glass house. He opened to a blank page. He closed his eyes and breathed. 

"What are you?"

The ink took time to appear. It pooled slowly onto the page. 

The faceless one stands on a mountain peak. The sky burns. 

Before Matthis could make sense of this, more ink formed. 

The faceless one stands on a balcony. The sea dries out. The mountains melt. 

The faceless one watches men and women scream. The earth cracks open. The sun goes out. 

Matthis tapped the page. The moon behind him cast a shadow that grew longer and deeper. Only the stars remained. He thumbed to the beginning on the book. 

"Mne...mo...syne."

The wizard groaned. 